<article>
    <h1>Scar&#xAD;lett</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210103/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-03"><time>2021-01-03</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Where: Two out­lets at 01-01C, 20 Treng­ganu Street; and 290/292 Gey­lang Road; open: 24 hours daily</p>
    <p>Info: www.face­book.com/ SiJi­aKeisS­car­lett</p>
    <p>For those who have yet to catch on to the suan la fen (sour and spicy noo­dles) craze, this is the spot to snag a wide va­ri­ety to sam­ple at low prices. Three cups of the pop­u­lar Haichi­jia suan la fen, for ex­am­ple, cost $4 – about half the price com­pared with last year.</p>
    <p>Scar­lett, a lo­cal com­pany which sup­plies tourist sou­venirs, made its foray into supermarke­ts by open­ing in Chi­na­town in Oc­to­ber last year, fol­lowed by a se­cond out­let in Gey­lang in Novem­ber. By next month, it will open its third, a flag­ship out­let at Peo­ple’s Park Com­plex.</p>
    <p>It spe­cialises in prod­ucts from China. Apart from suan la fen, pick from a dizzy­ing ar­ray of tid­bits, sauces and drinks – in cre­ative pack­ag­ing with whim­si­cal Chi­nese catch­phrases.</p>
    <p>Look out for strik­ing snacks from China’s on­line re­tailer Three Squir­rels; spicy cray­fish-flavoured Lay’s potato chips ($1.65) from China; and luo si fen (river snail in­stant noo­dles, $2.85) – en­dorsed by Chi­nese food blog­ger and In­ter­net celebrity Li Ziqi.</p>
    <p>Show­ing The Sun­day Times around the store, Mr Terry Lee – Scar­lett’s head of com­mu­nity en­gage­ment – picked out pop­u­lar prod­ucts such as Chao Ba Ye’s xiao ma hua (fried dough twists), an old-school snack “made new again” with vi­brant pack­ag­ing and de­sign.</p>
    <p>“What is con­sid­ered tra­di­tional food now ap­peals to mil­len­ni­als,” ob­serves Mr Lee, who in­ter­acts with Scar­lett’s cus­tomers on so­cial me­dia plat­forms.</p>
    <p>It is his way of build­ing a “cul­tural con­nec­tion” be­tween Sin­ga­pore­ans and the Chi­nese, one snack at a time.</p>
    <p>In the fu­ture, he does not rule out ex­pand­ing into the heart­land and set­ting up an on­line shop.</p>

